To create a movie streaming website from scratch, you'll need to follow these steps:

1. Set up Heroku to host your APIs

First, you'll need to create the backend RESTful APIs for your website. These APIs will act as a communication layer between your frontend (Webflow) and your backend (Heroku). You'll need to perform actions such as fetching movies, adding new movies, and so on.

Step 1.1: Sign up for Heroku and create a new app

- Sign up for a free account on Heroku (https://signup.heroku.com)
- After signing up, go to your dashboard (https://dashboard.heroku.com/apps) and click on "Create new app"
- Give your app a name (e.g., kritica-movies), and choose a region (United States or Europe)
- Click on "Create app"

Step 1.2: Set up your repository

- Install Node.js in your local machine, if you haven't done so already (https://nodejs.org/en/download/)
- Install the Heroku CLI (https://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/heroku-cli)
- Create a new folder for your project, e.g. `movie-api`
- Inside the folder, initialize a new Node.js project with the command:
```
npm init -y
```

- Install the required dependencies for your API using npm
```
npm install express mongoose cors
```
- Set up your API structure by creating three main files: index.js (for the main server setup), routes.js (for defining API routes and associated functions), and .env (for storing environment variables such as database connections)

index.js:
```
const express = require('express');
const cors = require('cors');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const routes = require('./routes');

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false }));
app.use(cors());

// Set up your environment variables (for the database connection) in the .env file
require('dotenv').config();
mongoose.connect(process.env.MONGODB_URL, { useNewUrlParser: true, useUnifiedTopology: true });
mongoose.set('useCreateIndex', true);

app.use('/', routes);

app.listen(process.env.PORT || 3000, () => {
  console.log('Server started on port http://localhost:' + (process.env.PORT || 3000));
});
```



Step 1.3: Set up the database for your movie streaming website

- Sign up for a free MongoDB Atlas account (https://www.mongodb.com/cloud/atlas/signup)
- Create a new cluster and a new database user with a strong password
- Create a new database and a new collection (`movies`) within that database
- Create a new .env file in your local repository and add the following code (replace the placeholders with your actual values):
```
MONGODB_URL=mongodb+srv://<YOUR_USERNAME>:<YOUR_DATABASE_PASSWORD>@<YOUR_MONGO_DB_CLUSTER_NAME>.mongodb.net/test?retryWrites=true&w=majority
PORT=8080
```

Step 1.4: Create the API endpoints for your movie streaming website

routes.js:
```
const express = require('express');
const { getMovies, addMovie } = require('./controllers/movieController');

const router = express.Router();

// Define the API endpoints
router.get('/movies', getMovies);
router.post('/movies', addMovie);

module.exports = router;
```

- Create the controller that handles database operations (`getMovies`, `addMovie`)
movieController.js:

```
const Movie = require('./models/movieModel');

exports.getMovies = async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const movies = await Movie.find();
    res.status(200).json(movies);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: `Error getting movies: ${error}` });
  }
};

exports.addMovie = async (req, res) => {
  const { title, description, imageUrl, videoUrl } = req.body;
  const newMovie = new Movie({ title, description, imageUrl, videoUrl });

  try {
    const savedMovie = await newMovie.save();
    res.status(201).json(savedMovie);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: `Error adding movie: ${error}` });
  }
};
```

- Create the schema for the `Movie` model
movieModel.js:

```
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const MovieSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  title: { type: String, required: true },
  description: { type: String, required: true },
  imageUrl: { type: String, required: true },
  videoUrl: { type: String, required: true },
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('Movie', MovieSchema);
```

Step 1.5: Configure Heroku to use your MongoDB database connection
- Go to your Heroku app dashboard (https://dashboard.heroku.com/apps/your-app-name/settings)
- Click on the "Reveal Config Vars" button and add the following key-value pairs:
  - MONGODB_URL: (your MongoDB Atlas connection string)
  - PORT: 8080

Step 1.6: Deploy your API to Heroku
- Commit your changes (in the `movie-api` folder) using Git:
   ```
   git init
   git add .
   git commit -m "First commit"
   ```
- Connect your local Git repository to the remote Heroku app:
   ```
   heroku git:remote -a your-app-name
   ```
- Deploy your API to Heroku:
   ```
   git push heroku master
   ```
- You should now have a working API endpoint for fetching movies: `https://your-app-name.herokuapp.com/movies`

